Introduction to the assignment:

  • The goal here is to make a really great, informative, and accurate plot with any set of data. Conversely, we will also be making a horrible plot both in its aesthetics and accuracy of portrayed data.

Load Libraries

library(tidyverse)
library(here)
library(magick)
library(PNWColors)

Read in Data

This dataset is downloaded from the NSF-funded Moorea Coral Reef Long-Term Ecological Research project in Moorea, French Polynesia.

This dataset is part of a time-series study which includes recruitment data from 2005 through 2016 and uses ceramic tiles to collect and count coral recruits from the lagoon and the forereef. Primary families of coral species were Acroporids, Pocillopora, and Porites, with some labeled as other or unidentifiable.

#read in the data from MCR!

coral_counts2 <- coral_counts %>% 
  filter(family!="Unidentified", 
         family!="Other",

  drop_na() %>% 
  mutate(season=if_else(season=="jan-sep","Jan-Sep", "Sep-Jan"))

Make a good plot

This is a good plot because it very clearly illustrates the data in a straightforward and accurate way. This plot shows the two recruitment seasons on the x-axis and the total counts of recruits across all years of the study on the y-axis. The plot is faceted by coral family to show a direct comparison between each one. It also includes a helpful figure caption and a picture in the top right corner of what a recruitment tile looks like for reference. The labels are easy to read and the title clearly explains what the plot is showing.

ggplot(data=coral_counts3, 
       aes(x=season, 
           y=sum_total, 
           fill=season)) + 
  geom_col() + 
  facet_wrap(~family) + 
  theme_linedraw() + 
  scale_fill_manual(values=pnw_palette("Sailboat")) +
  labs(x="Recruitment Season", 
       y="Total number of coral recruits", 
       title="Species abundance of coral recruits by season from 2005-2016", 
       fill="Season") + 
  theme(axis.text.x=element_text(size=10), 
        axis.text.y=element_text(size=10), 
        axis.title.x=element_text(size=12),
        axis.title.y=element_text(size=12), 
        plot.title=element_text(hjust=0.5))

This plot shows the total counts from 2005-2016 for coral recruits on collected tiles across all habitats and shores.

Make a bad plot

This is a bad plot because … well hopefully it is obvious.
But, aside from the obvious bold choice of colors, the axis labels are too big to read effectively and the title is small and off-center. Also the actual data, is facet wrapped in potentially a helpful way except that no context is really given for what we are looking at. There is count data on the y axis, but for what? And there is virtually no context for what or where these lagoon or forereef areas are. Also, the axes are scaled inappropriately (how would there be negative recruits?) and therefore puts the data crunched in the middle of the graph. The line shapes are also too crowded together to actually see the data.

ggplot(data=coral_counts, 
       aes(x=nominal_year, 
           y=count)) +
  geom_segment(aes(x=nominal_year, xend=nominal_year, y=0, yend=count)) +
  geom_point(size=2, color="yellow", fill=alpha("green", 0.1), alpha=0.7, shape=21, stroke=2) +
  facet_wrap(shore~habitat) + 
  theme_gray() + 
  labs(x="year", 
       y="number", 
       title="RECRUIT SPP IN 2000s ") +
  theme(axis.text.x=element_text(size=20), 
        axis.text.y=element_text(size=20), 
        axis.title.x=element_text(size=5),
        axis.title.y=element_text(size=8),
        plot.title=element_text(hjust=1, size = rel(0.8) ), 
        plot.background=element_rect("hotpink"), 
        panel.border=element_rect(fill = NA, colour = "blue"), 
        strip.background = element_rect(fill = "orange", colour = "purple")) + 
  xlim(2000,2020) + 
  ylim(-20,50)

This is a really bad plot that illustrates the counts of coral families (unlabeled) on recruitment tiles in different habitats and shores in Moorea from 2005-2016
